PCL200H1-F-20209.courseDescription:
Lectures introduce students to prescribed and illicit drugs that affect the brain. Lectures cover drug pharmacology and explain how drugs alter mood, perception, cognition, and arousal by affecting different aspects of brain function. The societal impact of these prescribed and illicit drugs is also discussed.


Note: This course is not intended for upper year students who have already completed BCH210H1 or other exclusion courses. Upper year Life Science students who are excluded and are interested in this content should look into PCL475H1 and/or PCL476H1 as the more appropriate choice.
PCL200H1-F-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Amy Ramsey, a.ramsey@utoronto.ca. Please note this is a breadth course for students either outside of the Life Sciences or for students in year 1 interested in gaining an appreciation for drugs and the brain.
PCL200H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Course meetings will be delivered in a combination of online synchronous and asynchronous components. Each week the course will have 3 hours of contact time through a combination of these modalities. All term assessments will take place during scheduled course time.

PCL201H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Introduction to Pharmacology and Pharmacokinetic Principles
PCL201H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A general introduction to the principles of pharmacology and pharmacokinetics. Topics include chemical (drug) absorption, distribution, biotransformation, elimination; the calculation of dosages and pharmacokinetic parameters, variability in drug response, adverse drug reactions and special interest topics.
PCL201H1-S-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Cindy Woodland, cindy.woodland@utoronto.ca. Students in either Subject POsT code AEESCBASCO BASc-Engineering Sci (Nano Eng) or AEESCBASEB BASc in Eng Sci (Biomedical) will be provided exemption from required pre-requisite courses. Please contact course coordinator.
PCL201H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered fully online per the meeting schedule (synchronous). All term assessments will take place during scheduled course time.

PCL218H1-S-20209.courseDescription: There is a critical need for a breadth of understanding regarding its mechanism of action, pharmacological effects and its potential benefits and harms (short- and long-term). Students will gain a breadth of understanding in cannabis-related topics including pharmacology and toxicology, its role in mental health and addictions, medical use, drug policy and new drug development that stems from increased access to cannabis constituents. They will learn to differentiate myths and anecdotes from evidence-based knowledge. Going forward it is imperative that students spanning basic sciences through business, arts and engineering have a comprehensive understanding of these topics. PCL218H1 will give students for a variety of academic backgrounds a basic understanding of the health implications of cannabis which have broad implications for both our professional and personal lives.
PCL218H1-S-20209.webTimetableInstructions:
Student inquiries should be directed to the undergraduate office: undergrad.pharmtox@utoronto.ca 

Please note this is a breadth course for students either outside of the Life Sciences or for students in year 1 interested in gaining an appreciation for cannabis and its pharmacology and toxicology.
PCL218H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered fully online per the meeting schedule (synchronous). All term assessments will take place during scheduled course time.

PCL297H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A formal opportunity to gain hands-on experience and develop their skills within a research laboratory setting. Students will have a chance to become familiar and efficient at good lab practices, develop critical thinking and evaluation skills while applying their knowledge and developing trouble shooting skills to practical research questions. This course is Pass/Fail. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PCL297H1-S-20209.prerequisite: None; Permission of Faculty Supervisor and Departmental Undergraduate Coordinator required.
PCL297H1-S-20209.recommendedPreparation: Completion of at least first year of Life Sciences program.
PCL297H1-S-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Students enroll in this course through the Department. Please contact course coordinator: Dr. Hamadani at anita.hamadanizadeh@utoronto.ca
PCL297H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This is an independent research project course with no formal lecture schedule. Students are required to secure their own supervisor for the course. Health and safety guidelines and lab capacity will determine the delivery methodology (i.e., in-person vs. online) of the course work at the time of study.

PCL302H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Topics include biological action of drugs on membranes, enzymes, receptors, neural and hormonal systems, transmission and modulation.
PCL302H1-F-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Michelle Arnot, michelle.arnot@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

Some lectures may be fully online per the syllabus. Each week the course will have 3 hours of contact time through a combination of these modalities. PCL345H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Lecturers use their own research to demonstrate how they approach a biological question. The lectures emphasize why one approach is chosen over other possible approaches, and explain the strengths and limitations of techniques. Following the one-hour lecture there is an interactive discussion of the experimental approach covered in the lecture.
PCL345H1-S-20209.prerequisite: One of PSL300H1/PSL301H1/BIO270H1/BIO271H1, and completion of at least 10.0 FCE, or permission of Department
PCL345H1-S-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Ana Andreazza, ana.andreazza@utoronto.ca.
PCL345H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered fully online per the meeting schedule (synchronous). All term assessments will take place during scheduled course time.

PCL362H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Toxicological problems encountered in animals and humans; biochemical mechanisms and clinical factors of toxicological significance; models of drug-related diseases.

PCL368H1-F-20209.courseTitle: Drug Development Pipeline II:  In vivo
PCL368H1-F-20209.courseDescription: This course will provide a learning experience that parallels and simulates the process, protocols, methods and evaluation tools used for later-stage in vivo drug development. Modules will build on the students fundamental knowledge and simulate the thought processes and techniques used during drug development in research institutes, clinical research organizations and pharmaceutical and biotechnology companies worldwide. Modules will include pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic analyses and pharmacogenetic screening approaches in model systems and humans. This experience will allow students to leverage their learned skills and knowledge to improve their comprehension and employability in this area, while honing critical thinking and analytical skills.
PCL368H1-F-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Anita Hamadani, anita.hamadanizadeh@utoronto.ca.
PCL368H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions:
LEC0101: Course content will be delivered fully online (synchronous, with some asynchronous components as indicated in the course syllabus).

LEC0201: Course content will be delivered primarily in-person as health guidelines permit.

PCL389H1-F-20209.courseTitle: Understanding the Role of Pharmacology and Toxicology in Society
PCL389H1-F-20209.courseDescription: This service learning course explores issues surrounding the effects that pharmaceuticals and chemicals have in society. Specifically, it integrates pharmacology and toxicology with social, health and political issues as they relate to drug abuse and addiction. Students are required to interact and work with community partners during the semester (approx 20hrs). Classroom discussions will integrate community experiences with lecture material.
PCL389H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered remotely in an online synchronous format only. Students must be available to participate in the course during scheduled class time, as no lecture recordings will be made available (i.e., asynchronous delivery is not available for this course).

PCL402H1-F-20209.courseTitle: Pharmacology and Toxicology in Drug Development
PCL402H1-F-20209.courseDescription: This course provides the basic principles of drug development, with a primary focus on the application of fundamental principles of pharmacology and toxicology to the design and conduct of early phase clinical trials. This is the phase of the drug development process where much of the innovation and science occurs.
PCL402H1-F-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Rebecca Laposa, rebecca.laposa@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.
PCL402H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions:
Course meetings will be delivered in a combination of in-person and streamed online, as well as asynchronous components (i.e., lectures will be delivered online asynchronously each week accompanied by a synchronous tutorial in-person or online). All term assessments will take place during scheduled course time.

TUT0101/TUT9101: Dual-delivery

TUT0201/TUT9201: Online Synchronous Only

PCL469H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A culmination of pharmacological principles discussing concepts of drug properties and their interactions within the body. The mechanism of action, pharmacological properties including clinical use and adverse effects of drugs acting on the autonomic nervous systems, cardiovascular, renal, respiratory, gastrointestinal and endocrine systems will be examined. Critical evaluation of primary literature and examination of clinical problem-based case studies will be integrated with lecture material through small group sessions.
PCL469H1-S-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Michelle Arnot, michelle.arnot@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.
PCL469H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures are delivered with an option to attend either in-person (as health guidelines permit) or online live-streamed per the meeting schedule (synchronous). Some lectures may be fully online per the syllabus. All term assessments will take place during scheduled course time.

PCL470H1-F-20209.courseDescription: A culmination of pharmacological principles discussing concepts of drug properties and their interactions within the body. The mechanism of action, pharmacological properties including clinical use and adverse effects of drugs acting on the central nervous systems and immunological system; antimicrobial and cancer chemotherapeutic agents as well as the potential therapeutic use of endogenous/herbal compounds will be examined. Critical evaluation of primary literature and examination of clinical problem-based case studies will be integrated with lecture material through small group sessions.
PCL470H1-F-20209.prerequisite: PCL201H1, PCL302H1, (PSL300H1, PSL301H1), a minimum of 14 FCE or Permission of the Department.
PCL470H1-F-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Ali Salahpour, ali.salahpour@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.
PCL470H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered fully online synchronous with some online asynchronous components. Small group sessions will run online synchronously during scheduled lecture time.

PCL472Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: This course affords students an opportunity for hands-on research experience in a laboratory or applied pharmacology setting. Students will work under the supervision of a faculty member and will submit a final written report and oral presentation. Enrollment is limited and requires permission from the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology. It is the students responsibility to secure a placement with an approved supervisor before the course begins (a list of potential supervisors can be obtained from the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology). Students will be registered in the course once their ballot form (obtained from the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology) is signed by an approved supervisor and approved by the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology. Students are expected to spend approximately 200 hours towards this project but this will be project/supervisor dependent. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PCL472Y1-Y-20209.prerequisite: PCL201H1, PCL302H1, PCL366H1/PCL367H1/PCL368H1, STA288H1/PCL376H1, and permission of Department
PCL472Y1-Y-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Students enroll in this course through the Department. Please contact Dr. Laposa at pharmtox.research.project@utoronto.ca
PCL472Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions:
LEC0101 - learning for this course is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. There are no formal lecture meetings as part of this course.

TUT0101/9101 - Tutorials will be delivered online per the meeting schedule/syllabus with the option of in-person (with parallel online) delivery (as health guidelines permit).

PCL475H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Students will explore the major CNS neurological syndromes, examples include pain, epilepsy, the sleep-wake cycle and relate neurological abnormalities. Lectures will discuss major classes of drugs used to mitigate and treat these disorder, their mechanisms of action, clinical use and unwanted effects. This course was previously offered as PCL475Y1.

PCL475H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered fully online per the meeting schedule (synchronous). All term assessments will take place during scheduled course time.

PCL476H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Students will explore the major CNS neurological syndromes which may include anxiety, schizophrenia and depression/mania and their relate neurological abnormalities. Lectures will discuss major classes of drugs used to mitigate and treat these disorders, their mechanisms of action, clinical use and unwanted effects.

PCL477H1-F-20209.courseTitle: The DNA Damage Response in Pharmacology and Toxicology
PCL477H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Many anticancer drugs and environmental agents exert their cytotoxic effects through DNA damage. This course explores specific pharmacological and toxicological agents that damage DNA and discusses how mammalian cells respond to this DNA damage.
PCL477H1-F-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Peter McPherson, peter.mcpherson@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.
PCL477H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered with an option to attend either in-person (as health guidelines permit) or online live-streamed per the meeting schedule (synchronous). Some lectures may be fully online per the syllabus.

PCL481H1-S-20209.courseTitle: The Molecular and Biochemical Basis of Toxicology
PCL481H1-S-20209.courseDescription: The biochemical principles and molecular mechanisms underlying the toxicity of drugs and foreign agents. The sequence of events at the molecular level leading to impairment of cell function and the factors which determine and affect toxicity.
PCL481H1-S-20209.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to undergrad.pharmtox@utoronto.ca Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.
PCL481H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures are delivered with an option to attend either in-person (as health guidelines permit) or online live-streamed per the meeting schedule (synchronous). Lectures cover principles of toxicology, the mechanisms of toxicity of a wide variety of toxic agents and the associated toxicities, methodologies used to examine chemical toxicities, risk assessment, and the applications of toxicology.

Students will integrate lecture material with assigned readings and assignments.
